title: Donald Trump provides insight into peace talks with Ukraine
description: US President Donald Trump spoke on Air Force One about the peace talks in Florida between US officials and Ukrainian officials.  “They’re going along well,” President Trump said.  “We want to stop people from being killed.  “I think Russia would like to see it end, and I know Ukraine would like to see it end.”

title: Rachel Reeves denies claims she misled the public about her budget
description: UK Chancellor Rachel Reeves insists she did not mislead the public about the state of the public finances in the build-up to her budget.  Ms Reeves announced several tax rises last week in an attempt to solve financial issues, but reports have emerged that the UK Prime Minister’s office was also aware of these economic forecasts.  Conservative Leader Kemi Badenoch went on the attack, saying she is doing a “terrible job” and has made a “mess of the economy”.

title: eSafety Commissioner announces major initiatives to reduce online harm
description: eSafety Commissioner Julie Inman Grant has unveiled new government initiatives to increase efforts to reduce online harm, including the world’s first national technology-facilitated abuse service.

title: AEMO warns of east coast blackouts if Eraring closes in 2027
description: The Australian Energy Market Operator warns the east coast could face blackouts if the nation’s biggest coal-fired power station closes in 2027.  The nation’s largest coal-fired plant, Eraring Power Station in New South Wales, is scheduled to cease operations in 2027.

title: Donald Trump ‘not going to play nice anymore’ with Nicolas Maduro
description: Political analyst Joe Siracusa weighs in on reports US President Donald Trump has given Venezuelan President Nicolas Maduro a chance to escape the country with his life.  “What he wants is, he wants global amnesty,” Mr Siracusa told Sky News Australia.  “If he wants to go, he wants to go with his money, and he wants to make sure he doesn’t get arrested anywhere, and Trump’s not going to do that.  “This is what we call military diplomacy, they’re going to do through military means what they haven’t been able to do, in other words, they’re not going to play nice anymore.”

title: Antifa protesters blasted with water cannons during demonstration of hard-right German party
description: Thousands of Antifa protesters clashed with police on Saturday after delaying a conference for a German right-wing political party.  According to Fox News, 25,000 to 30,000 activists held a protest targeting the youth wing of the Alternative for Germany (AfD), called Generation Deutschland.  The tens of thousands of activists turned out to protest a founding convention for the AfD youth group in the city of Giessen.  The protest saw the deployment of 6,000 officers, the largest police contingent in the state of Hesse's history, according to Fox News.  The protests turned violent as activists clashed with police, forcing officers to deploy pepper spray after stones were thrown at them, authorities said.  Police also deployed water cannons on roughly 2,000 far-left activists after they ignored orders to disperse.

title: Labor needs to ‘urgently’ tackle the threat of looming blackouts
description: Grattan Institute Energy Program Senior Fellow Tony Wood weighs in on the East Coast facing blackouts if the nation’s biggest coal-fired power station closes in 2027.

title: TikTok’s plan to build major Australian data centres continues to be stalled
description: TikTok’s plan to build major data centres in Australia has stalled because the company has failed to secure Foreign Investment Review Board approval for more than a year.  TikTok has been seeking proposals from local operators to construct a 100-megawatt facility in New South Wales or Victoria.  Its application has not progressed over concerns of foreign ownership of critical infrastructure.

title: Firefighters extinguish bushfires in parts of New South Wales
description: A bushfire in Sydney’s Northern Beaches has now been contained.  Crews had been trying to control the blaze in Allambie Heights since Sunday evening.  The Rural Fire Service has also been trying to contain a fire in the Goulburn River National Park.  More than 800 hectares have been destroyed so far.

title: Tasmania’s proposed stadium sees 15,000 people rallying their support
description: Thousands of AFL fans descended on Hobart to show support for the proposed Macquarie Point Stadium.  Decades after it was first proposed, the development phase is a final vote in Tasmania’s Upper House later this week.   The fans packed the lawns of Tasmania’s parliament, urging Upper House politicians to back the proposed $1 billion stadium, which can seat up to 23,000 people.  Supporters say the stadium will be more than a footy field, but also for cricket field and concerts, and will create thousands of jobs.

title: Sussan Ley declines to back David Littleproud amid Barnaby Joyce’s resignation
description: Opposition Leader Sussan Ley is refusing to back Nationals Leader David Littleproud as he navigates a very public fallout with New England MP Barnaby Joyce.  Mr Joyce quit the party to sit as an independent, but is not ruling out joining One Nation.  He publicly criticised Mr Littleproud and Nationals Deputy Leader Kevin Hogan during his resignation speech.  He claimed he had no communication from either of them to resolve the conflict.  Ms Ley says she had spoken to Mr Joyce but had made no attempt to persuade him not to join One Nation.

title: Mark Kelly doubles down on unhinged calls to defy President Trump's orders
description: Democratic Senator Mark Kelly has doubled down on his call for military members to defy unlawful orders from US President Donald Trump.  Kelly went on NBC’s Meet the Press to discuss his opinion on the Trump administration’s strikes on alleged drug boats.  The Arizona senator said that President Trump and Defence Secretary Pete Hegseth are “not serious people.”  This comes after Defence Department officials said they were launching an investigation into Kelly after Donald Trump accused him and several other lawmakers of “seditious behaviour.”  “This president thinks he can bully and intimidate people, and he is not going to, he’s not going to stop me from speaking out and holding him accountable for the things that he does that are wrong and unlawful,” Kelly told NBC News’ ‘Meet the Press’.  This comes as US President Donald Trump has declared that the airspace above and around Venezuela should be closed.

title: ‘We’re still going into the brick wall’: US must overcome Putin obstacle to end Ukraine war
description: Sky News US analyst Michael Ware discusses the meeting between US and Ukrainian officials in Florida as part of American efforts to end the war.  “At best, hopefully the Trump administration and the Ukrainians have been able to drill down to the very key points that they both can agree on,” he told Sky News Australia.  “We’re still going into the brick wall – running to the brick wall that is Vladimir Putin.”

title: Josh Brolin hails Donald Trump a ‘marketing genius’, reflects on past friendship with president
description: Hollywood actor Josh Brolin has opened up about his past with Donald Trump before the president’s time in the White House.  During an interview with The Independent on Saturday, Brolin hailed Trump a “marketing genius” and dispelled rumours about a third Trump term.  “I’m not scared of Trump, because even though he says he’s staying forever, it’s just not going to happen. And if it does, then I’ll deal with that moment. But having been a friend of Trump before he was president, I know a different guy,” Brolin said.  Both men met during the actor’s appearance in ‘Wall Street: Money Never Sleeps’, where he spoke to Trump about building his tower in New York.  “There is no greater genius than him in marketing – he takes the weakness of the general population and fills it. And that’s why I think a lot of people feel that they have a mascot in him,” Brolin said.

title: Labor records its worst-ever result in North Queensland by-election
description: The Crisafulli government has picked up a seat in North Queensland in a by-election victory which saw Labor record its worst ever result.  It’s also left the Katter Party’s representation in the state parliament down to just two seats.
